   <titleInfo>
      <title>Letter, John Shrady in Cincinnati, Ohio, to Jeannie Shrady in New York, N.Y., 1863 July 29</title>
   </titleInfo>
   <abstract>In this letter, dated July 29, 1863, from Cincinnati, Ohio, John Shrady, a regimental surgeon, writes to his wife, Jeannie, in New York City, relating to her the story of an "Indian-like massacre" of Union soldiers at Guyandotte, Virginia (now part of Huntington, West Virginia) in 1861. He opines that the "the spirit of the rebellion" turns men into "fiends," but he also considers the Confederates to be "abject cowards" when under the power of Union soldiers. The bulk of the letter is concerned with Shrady's hopes for the future, once the war has finished.</abstract>
